Why does printing e give a message (not hashcode)?

When you do:

System.out.println(e);


Internally, Java calls:

System.out.println(e.toString());


And Throwable (the parent of all exceptions) overrides toString() like this:

public String toString() {
    String s = getClass().getName();
    String message = getLocalizedMessage();
    return (message != null) ? (s + ": " + message) : s;
}


So for ArithmeticException: / by zero,

getClass().getName() → "java.lang.ArithmeticException"

getLocalizedMessage() → "/ by zero"

➡️ Result =

java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero